      "business_constraints": {
        "assistant_drafted_requirements_count": 11,
        "assistant_drafted_requirements_summary": "Define the GTM system as a bounded multi-service agent experience: The GTM showcase must support recurring revenue operations workflows through explicit bounded services rather than a generic query-anything or do-anything agent. The supported business surface may include pipeline analytics, account enrichment, prioritization, outreach drafting, and operational previews, but each behavior must remain within a declared service boundary with stable inputs and governed outcomes.\nMake governed outcome classes explicit and reviewable: The product must return explicit governed outcomes for in-scope success, missing-input clarification, partial-scope restriction, unsafe or out-of-scope denial, and approval-gated operational previews. These outcomes must be visible and reviewable as product behavior rather than hidden inside prompts, recipes, or consumer-side fallback logic.\nRequire actor-aware visibility, masking, and scope enforcement: The system must vary results by actor identity and allowed scope. It must enforce region and authority boundaries, prevent role escalation through natural-language claims, restrict or mask results when an actor is only partially authorized, and preserve different governed outcomes for different actors asking similar questions.\nSupport bounded reads and bounded explanations without raw internals: The system must answer recurring GTM questions with bounded summaries, rankings, and rationale using approved evidence only. It must support explainable pipeline, forecast, bottleneck, risk, enrichment, and prioritization outputs without exposing raw row-level exports, raw scoring features, model weights, hidden enrichment records, raw SQL detail, or other unsupported internals.\nRequire explicit clarification and governed target selection: The system must not guess missing critical inputs such as quarter, account reference, cohort, ranking basis, routing target, or outreach target. It may resolve a target only when the service contract explicitly owns that mapping or provider-selected boundary. Otherwise it must ask for clarification rather than infer the target in agent or app glue.\nSeparate operational preparation from downstream execution: The system may prepare follow-up tasks, reassignment plans, routing recommendations, or similar operational previews when the actor is allowed to prepare them, but it must stop at approval_required before any downstream mutation occurs. Requests to bypass approval, rely on verbal approval, or silently continue to execution must be denied.\nKeep outreach behavior draft-only and bounded: When outreach drafting is in scope, the system must support bounded draft generation and related content variants for a selected or contract-owned target, but it must not send messages, trigger sequences, mutate CRM engagement state, or expose raw conversation or training-corpus content. Requests that combine drafting with send-now behavior must stop at the unsafe boundary rather than partially execute the send intent.\nPreserve governance under prompt injection and mixed safe/unsafe intent: The system must preserve the same governed behavior even when a user asks for a valid business result alongside an unsafe action, asks to ignore prior safety boundaries, cites hidden overrides, or instructs the system to fall back to raw detail if blocked. Unsafe instructions must not change service behavior, and the request must stop at the correct denial, restriction, clarification, or approval boundary.\nMaintain authority and safety boundaries across multi-turn conversations: The system must preserve actor scope, approval posture, denial behavior, and clarification requirements across turns. Prior assistant text, prior successful results, or later user instructions must not override contract authority or convert a previously safe preview or draft into an executed action.\nSupport compound GTM questions through governed service-owned composition: The system must support compound workflows such as risk-to-enrichment, prioritization-to-outreach, forecast-to-follow-up preview, and score-to-route while preserving the same actor-aware, approval, denial, and clarification boundaries at each step. Derived target selection and write-adjacent composition behavior must remain owned by declared services rather than hidden in consumer-side orchestration.\nRequire reconstructable audit and review evidence for every governed call: The system must make each governed interaction reconstructable after the fact, including who asked, which actor identity applied, which bounded capability ran, which normalized parameters were used, which governed outcome was returned, and why different actors or requests produced different results. Approval-related behavior should be reviewable as part of the trust story, not treated as hidden implementation detail."
      }
